# QA Check Procedure

## When to Run QA

- After completing all tasks in a task pack
- When the user asks for a health check or QA review
- Before declaring any non-trivial work complete

## Steps

1. Read `.agentic/workflow/templates/qa-report-template.md`
2. Determine which checks apply to this project (read `.agentic/context/technical-context.md` for stack info)
3. Run each applicable check:
   - **Lint** — run the project's linter
   - **Type check** — run type checker if applicable (tsc, mypy, etc.)
   - **Build** — run the build command
   - **Unit tests** — run test suite
   - **Integration tests** — if available
   - **Accessibility** — if it's a web UI
   - **Smoke tests** — manual verification of key flows
4. Create a QA report in `.agentic/workflow/qa/` named `QA-NNN-<slug>.md`
5. Document results honestly — failures are valuable information
6. Report findings to the user

## When Checks Fail

- Document the failure in the QA report
- Assess severity (critical / high / medium / low)
- Fix critical and high issues before declaring done
- Medium and low issues can be noted for follow-up

## Project Mode Influence

| Mode | QA Strictness |
|------|--------------|
| New | Core checks (lint, build, basic tests) |
| Active | Standard (lint, types, build, unit tests) |
| Mature | Full suite including regression awareness |
| Legacy | Full suite plus extra caution on existing behavior |
